Science of The Total Environment

Volume 764, 10 April 2021, 144439

Flood risk influenced by the compound effect of storm surge and rainfall under climate change for low-lying coastal areas

Author links open overlay panel, , , , , ,
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.scitotenv.2020.144439Get rights and content

  • â€¢

  • â€¢

Abstract

Under climate change, compound flooding has resulted in severe disasters in coastal areas around the world. In this study, an integrated framework is proposed to determine the range of compound flood risk without the requirement of joint probability analysis between storm surge and rainfall. In the framework, the flood risks are analyzed under four extreme scenarios with/without the compound effect of storm surge and rainfall in the past and the future. From the end of the 20th century to the middle of the 21st century, the worst scenario shows that the flood area significantly increases by 92% for the low-lying coastal areas in southwest Taiwan under the compound effect of storm surge and rainfall if they are fully correlated. In the most optimistic scenario, the flood area slightly increases by 15% without compound effect (only storm surge is considered). To coastal flooding, the synchronization of storm surge and rainfall contributes much more than the climate-induced amplification of individual factors. When storm surge and rainfall happen at the same time, the extent and duration of flooding increase simultaneously under the influence of pluvial and surge-induced flooding. Risk analysis shows an obvious increase of risk level for villages originally at low risks, which require integrated countermeasures against the consequence brought by compound flooding in the future. The framework can be applied in other low-lying coastal areas to quantify the potential impacts on human and environment caused by compound flooding under climate change.

1. Introduction

Under the influence of global warming, the magnitudes of storm surge and rainfall raise simultaneously due to the increases of typhoon intensity, sea level, and seawater evaporation (Groisman et al., 2005; Wentz et al., 2007; Trenberth, 2011; Kulp and Strauss, 2019). In recent years, many compound flooding events from storm surge and rainfall have been observed such as in the Netherlands (Van den Hurk et al., 2015), Italy (Bevacqua et al., 2017), Australia (Kumbier et al., 2018), and United States (Valle-Levinson et al., 2020). All these events occurred within a few days due to sudden raises of sea level and rainfall caused by typhoon or low pressure systems near coastal areas. These compound flooding events are mainly caused by three mechanisms: (1) in estuarine areas where high river discharges and storm surges conjugate to elevate the water levels such as the cases in Australia and United States; (2) in coastal areas when an extreme storm surge occurs with a moderate rainfall, the flooding is mainly caused by seawater overtopping and then amplified by rainfall such as the case in Italy; and (3) when a heavy rainfall occurs with a moderate storm surge, the storm surge blocks or slows down the drainage so that enhances the pluvial flooding (Orton et al., 2012; Maskell et al., 2013). How to assess the compound flooding under climate change with joint considerations of scenarios, models, and impacts has become an important issue.

The dependence between storm surge and rainfall along with their influence on coastal flooding has been statistically confirmed during the last three decades (Pugh, 1987; Coles et al., 1999; Svensson and Jones, 2004). Zheng et al. (2013) quantified the flood risk for the Hawkesbury-Nepean catchment in Australia by three statistical models based on threshold excess, point process, and conditional methods, respectively. They found that the threshold-excess method generates more unbiased estimates than the others. Xu et al. (2014) found that the joint probability for storm surge and rainfall increased by 300% in Fuzhou City since 1984 under the influence of climate change. Wahl et al. (2015) demonstrated that the number of compound flooding instances has increased significantly in the past century at several major cities in United States. For New York City, the increase in compound flooding could be attributed to a shift of weather patterns that favor storm surge and high precipitation simultaneously. Zellou and Rahali (2019) assessed the risk of coastal flooding at the estuary of the Bouregreg River in Morocco, showing that the flood levels and extents can be seriously underestimated without considering the dependence between surge and rainfall.

In addition to joint statistical analysis, numerical coupling of circulation and hydraulic models is also crucial for the simulation of flooding caused by storm surge and rainfall. The circulation model calculates the storm surge along the coastline by taking into account the ocean, coastal, and estuarine water circulations; the hydraulic model simulates the inland inundation on watershed scale driven by upstream rainfall and downstream seawater level (Gallien et al., 2018). Cheng et al. (2010) coupled a nearshore model (ADCIRC, ADvanced CIRCulation model) and a watershed model [pWASH123D, parallel WAterSHed systems of 1D (one-dimensional) stream-river networks, 2D (two-dimensional) overland regimes, and 3D (three-dimensional) subsurface media] to improve the accuracy and stability of flow simulations for the Biloxi Bay in Mississippi. Tang et al. (2013) integrated a coastal ocean model (FVCOM, Finite Volume Community Ocean Model) with a Godunov-type shallow water model to predict the compound flooding under different storm scenarios for the east coast of Delaware Bay in New Jersey. Thompson and Frazier (2014) simulated the future flood hazards for the Sarasota County in Florida by integrating a 2D hurricane surge model (SLOSH, Sea, Lake and Overland Surges from Hurricanes model) and a 1D channel routing model (ICPR, Interconnected Channel and Pond Routing model). Joyce et al. (2018) conducted multi-scale flood assessment under the combined influence of storm tide and precipitation by coupling a nearshore wave transformation model (SWAN, Simulating WAves Nearshore model) with ADCIRC and ICPR for the Tampa Bay area in Florida.

Despite that the jointing of storm surge and rainfall has received attention, future risk assessment of compound flooding is still scarce in the literature because the computation is demanding if we try to take into account all possible climate change scenarios. In 2019, Bevacqua et al. (2019) analyzed the co-existence of sea level and precipitation in future climate and found an increasing trend of compound flooding along the northern European coast. However, their research analyzed the compound flooding on a continental scale without specific local conditions such as protection, population, and assets. For the studies that have included local vulnerability and exposure factors for risk analysis, coastal flooding related only to storm surge (Cristie et al., 2017; Sajjad et al., 2020) or sea level rise (Antunes et al., 2019; Dinh et al., 2012) without the compound effect with rainfall.

The literature review indicates a gap between the analysis of long-term surge-rainfall correlation and the prediction of local compound flood risk under climate change. This gap cannot be easily filled because it requires the integration of joint-probability theorem, numerical modelling, climate projection, and data processing to obtain the local flood risk under numerous combinations of storm surge and rainfall. The objective of this study is to propose an integrated and general framework for preliminary compound-flood-risk analysis before conducting sophisticated evaluations. This framework focuses on analyzing the upper and lower bounds of compound flooding based on only four scenarios of storm surge and rainfall in the past and future. Knowing the potential range and variance of compound flooding is valuable for deciding if further evaluation is necessary for coastal disaster reduction.

2. Study area

The study area (shown in Fig. 1) spans three counties in southwest Taiwan with a total area of 3671 km2. Within this area, 407 km2 has been officially designated as coastal areas (bounded by the dashed red line in Fig. 1). The study area borders the Taiwan Strait to the west, having a coastline of 173 km in southwest-northeast direction with mild beach slopes and a large tidal range between 1.19 m and 3.96 m. The topography descends rapidly from the high mountains above 3000 m in the west to the low-lying coastal areas in the east. There are 5 major rivers in this area, in which the largest one, Zhuoshui River, has a length of 187 km, a slope of 1/42, and a historical maximum discharge of 17,100 cm.

The study area frequently encountered large storm surges and rainfall during the rainstorm and typhoon seasons from April to October. In winter, the strong monsoon brings an average wind speed of 4.0 m/s mainly in a north-north-east direction. In Fig. 1, there are three important industrial parks located in the reclaimed lands in the coasts of Changhua and Yunlin Counties. Fish farming is a significant part of economy in the coastal areas, which has resulted in severe land subsidence accumulated up to 1.59 m and 1125 km2 due to decades of groundwater over-pumping. Under the influence of climate change, the study area has experienced multiple compound-flooding disasters and led to losses of millions USD (US dollars) in the last two decades as summarized in Table 1. Among them, Typhoon Morakot in 2009 brought the highest rainfall that exceeded 200-year return period and the highest storm surge with 50-year return period. More details about the study area can be referred to Hsu and Huang (2014).

3. Methodology

In this study, the variations of coastal flooding from the end of 20th century (named as â€œpastâ€ hereafter) to the middle of 21st century (named as â€œfutureâ€ hereafter) are analyzed. For the past and the future periods, the storm surge and rainfall under 50-year return period are determined using the climate data of 1981â€“2010 and 2036â€“2065, respectively. The 50-year return period is selected because it is the seawall design standard in Taiwan for storm surge protection. By analyzing the coastal flooding for 50-year return period, the protection capacity of the seawall system can be revaluated under the impact of climate change. A circulation model (SCHISM, Semi-implicit Cross-scale Hydroscience Integrated System Model; Zhang et al., 2016) and a hydraulic model (COS-Flow, Coupled Overland-Sewer Flow model; Jang et al., 2018; Jang et al., 2019) are coupled for coastal flood simulations under four (2 Ã— 2 = 4) hypothetical extreme scenarios: with/without compound effect in the past/future. The simulation results are processed and combined with socio-economic and environmental indexes to estimate the maximum possible variations of coastal flood risks in the four scenarios. The research framework is shown in Fig. 2, in which the orange boxes estimate the trends of storm surge and rainfall under climate projections; the blue boxes represent the numerical modelling implementation; and the green boxes denote the risk analysis. The details are described in the following sections.

3.1. Scenarios

The four hypothetical extreme scenarios are described in Table 2. Pt and Ft consider only the influence of storm surge on coastal flooding in the past and the future, respectively; Pt+r and Ft+r take into account both storm surge and rainfall for flood assessment in the past and the future, respectively. Statistically, Pt and Ft assume that storm surge and rainfall are independent, and the joint return period of coastal flooding equals to that of storm surge; Pt+r and Ft+r assume that storm surges are completely correlated to rainfall, so when the joint return period of coastal flooding reaches 50-year, storm surge and rainfall reach 50-year return period simultaneously. The Pt and Ft are named as â€œlower extreme scenariosâ€ hereafter because they provide the lower bounds of coastal flooding in the past and the future periods, respectively; the Pt+r and Ft+r are named as â€œupper extreme scenariosâ€ hereafter because they provide the upper bounds of compound flooding in the past and the future periods, respectively. The actual flooding for 50-year return period will lie somewhere between the lower and upper extreme scenarios because storm surge and rainfall are neither independent nor completely correlated in the real world.

Table 2. Scenarios for coastal flood assessment.

ScenarioPeriodJoint return periodFactors
PtPast50-year50-year storm surge
FtFuture50-year50-year storm surge
Pt+rPast50-year50-year storm surge + 50-year rainfall
Ft+rFuture50-year50-year storm surge + 50-year rainfall

3.2. Climate change predictions

3.2.1. Storm surge

To estimate the trends of storm surge (including the impacts of wave, tide, and sea level) under climate change, the wind and pressure data generated by 39 GCMs (General Circulation Models) in IPCC AR5 (Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, fifth assessment report; IPCC, 2013) are acquired for analysis. Three criteria are applied to select appropriate GCMs for circulation simulation: (1) data resolution should be finer than 6 h in time and 1.5Â° global grid in space; (2) atmospheric pressure at sea level is available; (3) RCP8.5 (Representative Concentration Pathway) scenario is included. The RCP 8.5 is selected because it represents the worst case with carbon dioxide (CO2) emissions continuing to rise throughout the 21st century. In total, 10 out of the 39 GCMs are selected, including the MRI-CGCM3, MIROC5, EC-EARTH, CMCC-CM, CCSM4, BCC-CSM1.1, ACCESS1.0, ACCESS1.3, CSIRO-Mk3.6.0, and NRM-CM5. The sea areas between 15 Â° N â€“ 45 Â° N and 115 Â° E â€“ 145 Â° E in the Western Pacific Ocean (WPO) are adopted as the simulation domain, in which a total of 864 (27 Ã— 32) GCM points are fed into the circulation model to simulate the wave and storm surge heights in the past and the future periods. This part of simulation is named as â€œregional simulationâ€ because it translates the GCM data into continuous predictions of wave and storm surge across the WPO region with a spatial resolution up to 1.4 km, which then provides the boundary conditions for nearshore simulation.

By applying frequency analysis for the results of regional simulation, the increase ratios of wave height and surge height under 50-year return period between the past and the future periods are obtained for each of the selected GCM, respectively. According to the suggestion by US Army Coastal Engineering Manual (CEM, 2011), the annual-maximum-selection method and the probability distribution functions Extreme Value I and Weibull are selected for fitness test in the frequency analysis. Finally, the increase ratios of wave and storm surge for the 10 GCMs are averaged and served for nearshore simulation. By using the average rather than the data from individual GCM or typhoon event, an unbiased prediction can be obtained because the typhoons around the Taiwan can come in different tracks with multiple combinations of strength and duration. It is difficult to identify one representative GCM or event for 50-year return period. As for sea level rise, the estimates are in the range of 2.44 â€“ 4.19 mm/y along the study coastline (Kuo et al., 2017).

Once the increments of wave, storm surge, and sea level are determined, they are superposed with the design hydrographs of wave and tide to serve as the boundary conditions (the model boundary is displayed in Fig. 1) for the SCHISM for â€œnearshore simulationâ€ of storm surge. The 24-hour design tide hydrograph is determined by the composition of a diurnal tide and a semidiurnal tide, in which the tide pattern is obtained by mixing the main tidal constituent M2 with the second and third constituents in harmonic analysis suggested by Lesser (2019). By adjusting the amplitudes in accordance with the tidal energy, the highest tide level of the design hydrograph approximately equals to the average of spring tide levels.

3.2.2. Rainfall

To analyze the rainfall increment under extreme greenhouse gas emissions, the monthly rainfall data generated by the GCMs (with a resolution of 250 km) under the RCP 8.5 scenario in IPCC AR5 (IPCC, 2013) are used. Out of the 33 GCMs, five GCMs (including bcc-csm1-1, HadGEM2-CC, IPSL-CM5A-MR, MPIESM-LR, and NorESM1-M) are adopted because they perform better in predicting different phases (onset, break, and revival) of East Asian summer monsoon that often produces substantial precipitation in Taiwan (Tung et al., 2020). By comparing GCM predictions with the estimations from long-term observation data, the monthly rainfall can be downscaled into daily rainfall by bias-correction and spatial disaggregation as proposed by Wood et al. (2004). The technique of rainfall downscaling can be found in Chen et al. (2014).

Through frequency analysis, the daily rainfall with resolution of 5 km under 50-year return period are determined for the five GCMs, which are then averaged to obtain the spatial distributions of daily rainfall in the past and the future. Since daily rainfall data are not sophisticated enough for high-precision hydraulic simulation, further downscaling along the time is required. By distributing the daily rainfall according to the dimensionless rainfall pattern obtained from historical rain-station data, the 24-hour design rainfall hyetographs can be determined for each grid cell in the past and the future.

3.3. Numerical model

The SCHISM and the COS-Flow models are offline coupled to simulate the coastal flooding for the four extreme scenarios. Using the wave and tide hydrographs obtained in Section 3.2.1, the SCHISM is triggered to determine the nearshore storm surge hydrographs, which are then introduced along with the rainfall hyetographs in Section 3.2.2 to initiate the COS-Flow. The two models are introduced as below.

3.3.1. Circulation model

To provide the downstream storm surge data for flood modelling, the circulation model should be able to simultaneously simulate the propagations of wave and storm surge from offshore zone to coastline. In light of the stability, efficiency, and the capability of dealing with dry/wet boundaries, the SCHISM has been widely used in simulating the wave propagation induced by tsunami (Zhang et al., 2011) and the overtopping caused by storm surge (Wang et al., 2014; Chen and Liu, 2016). Using semi-implicit finite element method, SCHISM adopts unstructured grid meshes and larger time steps regardless stability restrictions. In this study, the 2D depth-integrated version of SCHISM is adopted to reduce computational time. Based on hydrostatic and Boussinesq approximations, the SCHISM solves shallow water equations as below:(1)âˆ‚Î·âˆ‚t+âˆ‚uHâˆ‚x+âˆ‚vHâˆ‚y=0(2)DuDt=fvâˆ’âˆ‚âˆ‚xgÎ·âˆ’Î±Î¨^+PAÏo+Ï„sx+Ï„rx+Ï„bxÏoH=0(3)DvDt=fuâˆ’âˆ‚âˆ‚ygÎ·âˆ’Î±Î¨^+PAÏo+Ï„sy+Ï„ry+Ï„byÏoH=0where Î· denotes the elevation of free surface; H represents the total sea water depth; u and v are the flow velocities in x and y directions, respectively; f is the Coriolis parameter; g is the gravitational constant; Î¨^ is the tidal potential of earth; Î± is the effective elasticity of earth; Ïo stands for water density; PA depicts the atmospheric pressure; Ï„sx and Ï„sy denote the wind shear stresses in x and y directions, respectively; Ï„bx and Ï„by denote the bed shear stresses in x and y directions, respectively; Ï„rx and Ï„ry denote the wave radiation stresses in x and y directions, respectively.

For the nearshore simulation, the cell sizes are refined from 2 km in the offshore boundary to 25 m near the coastline with a total of 232,878 cells and 464,518 elements. For each cell, the elevation of sea bed is interpolated from the bathymetric data with 200 m resolution (ODB, 2013). Based on the formulation of the Joint North Sea Wave Project (JONSWAP, Hasselmann et al., 1973), the effective elasticity of earth Î± is set as 0.69. The time step is 10 s and the Manning's coefficient is set as 0.025 based on the sea bottom material in the calculation of bed shear stresses. The rest parameters are set following those in Hsiao et al. (2019).

3.3.2. Flood model

The COS-Flow is a self-developed model which has been well validated in previous studies for urban flood simulation (Jang et al., 2018; Jang et al., 2019). The COS-Flow realistically considers the interactions between rainfall, runoff, infiltration, sewer water, tide level, storm surge, and drainage based on physical mechanisms without simplifications. By using GIS (Geographic Information System) as the platform, the COS-Flow can easily communicate with the circulation model for data processing and result display. It combines a 2D overland flow module and a 1D channel flow module for simultaneously simulating the flow transport between land surface, river channels, sewer pipes, and detention ponds. The overland module adopts structure grid meshes and Alternate Direction Explicit (ADE) method to solve the dynamic wave form of shallow water equations, in which a source term is added in the mass equation to accept the water from the 1D module. To improve numerical precision in space and time, the ADE method solves Eqs. (4), (5), (6) alternatively in x and y directions, updating water depth and velocity every by half time steps under the Courant-Friedrichs-Lewy restrictions (Courant et al., 1967).

For the 1D module, the implicit backward Euler method (Ascher and Petzold, 1998) and Piscard iteration method (Picard, 1890) are adopted to solve the 1D Saint-Venant equation:(7)âˆ‚Aâˆ‚t+âˆ‚VAâˆ‚s=âˆ’QL(8)âˆ‚VAâˆ‚t+âˆ‚VAâˆ‚s=âˆ’gAâˆ‚hs+zsâˆ‚s+ns2VVR4/3where A denotes the cross-sectional area of flow in channels or pipes; V is the flow velocity in channels or pipes; L is the length of channels or pipes; R denotes the hydraulic radius; hs denotes the flow depth in channels or pipes; zs denotes the bottom elevations of channels or pipes; ns is the Manning's coefficient in s direction. In the COS-Flow model, the flow interaction between the 1D and 2D modules occurs in two conditions: (1) the overland water drains into the channel or pipes by gravity or pumping; and (2) the water in channels or pipes overflows and becomes overland flow. The details of the COS-Flow model can be found in Jang et al. (2018).

The discharge of Q is determined by weir or orifice equations according to the relative hydraulic heads between surface water and pipe flow (Lee et al., 2013). The structured mesh has 2,294,375 cells with cell size of 40 m, in which the elevation of bed topography z at each cell center is interpolated from the LiDar-derived DTM (Digital Elevation Model) data with 1 m resolution and 1 mm accuracy. To obtain the effective rainfall q, the runoff curve number method developed by US Department of Agriculture was used for calculating the infiltration under different land uses (NRCS, 2004). According to the suggestions by Chow (1959), the Manning's coefficients for the 2D module nx and ny are set as 0.035 while that for the 1D module ns is set as 0.017. The program code was parallelized via the Open Multi-Processing platform to speed up the simulation on multi-core computers.

3.4. Flood risk analysis

In the last two decades, the concept of Crichton's risk triangle (Crichton, 1999) has been widely used for disaster assessment (Thomalla et al., 2006; Collins et al., 2009; Kim et al., 2015) in which risk is evaluated by three components: Hazard, Exposure and Vulnerability. For coastal flooding, hazard represents the degree of harm caused by a flood event (Feng et al., 2020); exposure is the amounts of people or assets that exposed to flooding; vulnerability is the susceptibility of people or assets under flooding. In previous research, the three components are commonly evaluated by multiple indexes that can reflect local hydraulic, socio-economic, and environmental conditions, respectively (Fekete, 2009; Koks et al., 2015). Using multiple indexes helps to prevent biases because disaster reacts differently to local conditions such as population, education, income, and land use.

Considering the indexes adopted by previous researchers (Kavi Kumar and Tholkappian, 2006; Hong et al., 2006) and data availability, 2 hazard indexes, 4 exposure indexes, and 6 vulnerability indexes on village level are adopted for flood risk analysis as summarized in Table 3. The village is selected as the unit because flood alarms and domestic data are given by village in Taiwan. In the table, the hazard indexes, including the flood depth and flood area ratio, are evaluated by the hydraulic model; the exposure indexes are based on socio-economic conditions, including the population density, education level, dependency ratio, and commercial income; the vulnerability indexes incorporate the environmental conditions that may enhance the impact of flooding, i.e. the elevation, slope, tidal range, land subsidence rate, coastal erosion rate, and land use. Each index is given a weight obtained from Analytic Hierarchy Process (AHP; Saaty, 1980). The AHP is an effective technique for decision makers to decide the priority of indexes by reducing complex decision processes into a series of pairwise comparisons through questionnaire survey. In the survey, a total of 100 experts in different disciplines were involved and the consistency ratio of their feedbacks was checked according to the standard by Saaty (1980). More details about the AHP can be referred to Hsu and Huang (2014). By classifying each index into 5 levels according to the standards listed in Table 4 and taking weighted average of all the index levels in each component, the levels of hazard, exposure, and vulnerability can be determined for each village. After multiplying the three component levels (Dalezios, 2017), the risk scores are calculated and classified into 5 levels as well according to the rules in Table 4.

3.5. Performance indicator

4. Results

4.1. Validation of the numerical models

In Table 1, the Typhoon Megi occurred between Sep. 22 and Oct. 1 in 2016 and the low-pressure induced rainstorm between Aug. 23 and 24 in 2018 are adopted for validating the circulation and flood models, respectively. The two events are selected because they were the latest two events triggered by different climate systems but both resulted in great damages in the study area. The typhoon-induced event lasted longer so that the simulated storm surge can be evaluated in a longer period; the low-pressure event induced larger rainfall and severer flooding which makes it suitable for testing the flood model. For Typhoon Megi, the wind speed and pressure fields from ECMWF (European Centre for Medium-Range Weather Forecasts) with a time resolution of 6 h and a spatial resolution of 0.125Â° are used as input to trigger the SCHISM for nearshore storm surge simulation. The simulation wave heights are displayed in Fig. 3, which show good consistency with the observations with RMSE â‰¤ 0.11 m, WS â‰¥ 0.94 and NSE â‰¥ 0.71 as summarized in Table 5. As for the rainstorm event, the cumulative rainfall amounted to 716 mm, resulting in severe flooding especially in Chiayi County. Fig. 4 shows the simulated and observed flood areas in Chiayi County. The HIT reaches 0.75, meaning that 75% of the observed flood areas are correctly predicted by the COS-Flow model. In Taiwan, the observed flood areas are manually delineated by local governments from post-disaster investigations and interviews, which might contain some inaccuracies due to the losses of evidence and memory. Thus, some discrepancies between observation and simulation can be expected and HIT = 0.75 is considered acceptable. Overall, the validation results were satisfactory.

4.2. Increments of wave, storm surge, and rainfall under climate change

Fig. 5(a) and (b) shows the increase ratios of wave and storm surge in the WPO region from the past to the future under 50-year return period, which both show an increasing trend under the influence of climate change. The heights of wave and storm surge increases by 2% and 11% in the vicinity of the study coastline, respectively. The storm surges increase more than the waves and the increments are larger on the north side than on the south side of Taiwan. Fig. 6 displays the daily rainfall under 50-year return period in the past and the future. The rainfall increases in the future compared with that in the past, especially in the southern coastal regions. Fig. 7 shows the space-average 24-hour design hydrographs of tide and rainfall, obtained by taking average of the cell values on the ocean and land domains, respectively. The peaks of tide and rainfall are deliberately synchronized in the middle to maximum the compound effect.

4.3. Flood areas for different scenarios

For the four extreme scenarios, the design hydrographs of wave, tide, and rainfall are introduced into the SCHISM and COS-Flow for flood simulation. The simulated flood extents are displayed in Fig. 8, in which the flood areas are concentrated in the lower part of the coastal region along the coastline of Yunlin and Chiayi. The flood extent in Ft is slightly higher than that in Pt without compound effect. With compound effect, the flood extent in Ft+r becomes much larger than that in Pt, especially around the riverside areas where river overflow occurs due to the conjugation of upstream pluvial water and downstream surge water. Fig. 9 displays the temporal variations of flood areas for the four scenarios. The highest increase in peak flood area is 92% between Pt and Ft+r scenarios. The compound effect increases the peak flood areas by 70% (Pt vs. Pt+r) in the past and 66% (Ft vs. Ft+r) in the future. In contrast, the climate change only increases the peak flood areas by 15% (Pt vs. Ft) without compound effect and 13% (Pt+r vs. Ft+r) with compound effect.

In Fig. 9, the flooding shows different patterns with and without the compound effect. From 1 h to 7 h, no flooding occurred in Pt and Ft because the seawalls were higher than the storm surge levels. In contrast, the flooding in Pt+r and Ft+r started early due to the ponding of rainfall water. Between 8 h and 12 h, the flood areas in all scenarios increased rapidly since the storm surge and rainfall increased simultaneous (Fig. 7). As the surge and the rainfall dropped after 13 h, the flooding retreated but leaving large amounts of water accumulated in low-lying areas that cannot be easily drained by gravity. During this period, the flooding in Pt+r and Ft+r retreated much slowly because the rainfall-induced overland flow kept on flowing downstream.

4.4. Flood risk for different scenarios

Fig. 10 shows the levels of vulnerability and exposure for the villages in the study coastal areas, where the villages in the middle are relatively vulnerable due to land subsidence. Higher exposure levels are observed in the northern coastal areas where the industrial parks are located, which tend to have higher losses during flooding. After multiplying the vulnerability and exposure maps with the hazard map, the village-based flood risk maps for the four scenarios are obtained and shown in Fig. 11. All scenarios indicate that the coastal villages in Yunlin and Chiayi are at higher risk levels. Compared with the flooding caused by storm surge (Pt and Ft), the risk significantly increases under the compound effect of storm surge and rainfall (Pt+r and Ft+r). The flood risk in Erlin Village increases slightly under climate change regardless the compound effect. Fig. 12 shows the number of villages at each risk level for the four scenarios. Comparing Pt and Ft+r, the number of villages decreases significantly in level 1, increases significantly in level 2, and increases slightly in level 3â€“5. This implies that the villages that were originally at low risk will be more affected by compound flooding under climate change.

5. Discussion

5.1. Novelty and feasibility

The magnitude of compound flooding is dependent on the correlation between storm surge and rainfall, which is majorly evaluated from limited observed data and hypothetical climate projections. This results in large uncertainties in the flood risk predicted from the surge-rainfall correlation especially under high return periods. In this study, we did not try to evaluate the correlation between storm surge and rainfall using traditional joint probability analysis. We focused on developing a framework to analyze the compound flooding in four extreme scenarios by assuming the storm surge and rainfall are either fully dependent or fully independent. This method prevents the uncertainties in joint probability analysis because the probability of compound flooding directly equals to storm-surge probability in the four scenarios. Since all surge-rainfall combinations lies between the bounds defined by the four scenarios, this framework estimates the range of compound flooding for any return period regardless of joint probability analysis.

5.2. Uncertainty and limitation

The proposed framework estimates the range of compound flood risk for a local area, not the flood risk under any combinations of storm surge and rainfall. If the range between the two bounds is large, the compound effect is significant and a joint probability function (such as Copula; Sklar, 1959) is required to determine the flood risk under specific surge-rainfall conditions. The hypothetical carbon-concentration scenario RCP 8.5 adopted in this study represents the worst but not necessary the most realistic scenario. Other RCP scenarios such as RCP 2.6 (CO2 emissions decline since 2020 and reach zero by 2100), RCP 4.5 (CO2 emissions start declining by 2045 and reach half of the levels of 2050 by 2100), and RCP 6.0 (CO2 emissions peak around 2080 and then decline) can be included to evaluate the compound flood risk in an overall manner. Moreover, the assumption that the climate, land-use, socio-economic, and infrastructure conditions are unchanged in the future may also result in over- or under-estimations of flood risk.

5.3. Impacts of compound and non-compound flooding

Coastal flooding can be caused with or without the compound effects of storm surge and rainfall. The non-compound flooding induced by storm surge has different impacts from that caused by rainfall. The storm-surge-induced flooding is attributed to the overtopping of seawater, which may result in soil salinization, crop withering, infrastructure damage, and pipe corrosion. The rainfall-induced flooding comprises two forms: the pluvial flooding caused by local water accumulation and the fluvial flooding induced by high river discharges. The sea level rise will enhance the storm-surge-induced flooding by slowing down the river drainage in estuaries. The increase of rainfall will exacerbate the pluvial flooding in low-lying areas and the fluvial flooding in riverine areas due to the drainage blockage under high river stages. Under climate change, these phenomena can happen simultaneously and cause compound flooding much severer than independent flooding because of the spreading of inland water in coastal, low-lying, and riverine areas.

5.4. Future works

In the future, the proposed framework can be promoted to other coastal areas for evaluating the compound flood risk on a global scale. Some soft computing techniques such as machine learning methods can be applied to improve rainfall prediction (Homsi et al., 2020), river routing (Taormina and Chau, 2015; Gholami et al., 2016), flood simulation (Mosavi et al., 2018; Kaya et al., 2017), disaster management (Fotovatikhah et al., 2018), and the selection of vulnerability indexes (Islam et al., 2020). The implementation of remote sensing and imaging tools will benefit compound flooding analysis by gathering more data in coastal areas (Ali et al., 2020). Under climate change, some factors such as groundwater table rise may damage drainage pipes, reduce pond capacity, and thereby increase the compound flooding. Analyzing the pattern and the interaction between these factors in future climate will give a more in-depth concept about the impacts brought by compound flooding.

6. Conclusions

In this study, the coastal flood risk under climate change are analyzed for the low-lying areas on the southwest coast of Taiwan. To estimate the potential range of coastal flooding with/without the compound effect of storm surge and rainfall, four lower/upper extreme scenarios are set up for numerical simulation and risk analysis in the past (late 20th century) and in the future (mid-21st century). By coupling a circulation model and a hydraulic model, the results of IPCC GCMs are adopted to simulate the spatial and temporal variations of storm surge and coastal flooding under 50-year return period in the past and the future, respectively. The simulated flood results are converted into hazard indexes in combination with the vulnerability and exposure indexes to generate the village-based flood risk maps.

The numerical results reasonably predict the rise and retreat of coastal flooding along with the variations of storm surge and rainfall. The peak flood areas are estimated to increase up to 92% from the past to the future under the combined influences of climate change, storm surge, and rainfall. The flood areas increased by the compound effect of storm surge and rainfall are much larger than those by the influence of climate change, implying that future coastal flooding can be greatly underestimated without considering the compound effect. The overflow of river water and the decrease in drainage efficiency are the main reasons why compound flooding becomes more severe. For low-lying coastal areas, the flood duration extends because the water accumulated in depressions cannot be drained by gravity even on the low tides. The risk analysis shows that when the scenarios approach upper extremes, the villages originally at low risks tend to receive more impact than those originally at high risks.

The general framework proposed in this study can be applied in other coastal areas to preliminary evaluate the potential range of compound flooding, before sophisticated jointing of storm surge and rainfall can be realized for future climate. This information is particularly important for researchers interested in disaster prevention, environmental protection, and pollution transportation induced by severe coastal flooding. For the areas where flood risks may significantly increase in the future, an integrated strategy is required to speed up the drainage efficiency and reduce the consequence of compound flooding.
